buildingList.descriptionParagraph: Rocket Park is home to several examples of historic launch vehicles.
Building 4221 opened April 22 of 2019 as part of an effort for more of the center to be environmentally sustainable.
This is NASA's hub for advanced propulsion research and technology development at Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama.
The Redstone Test Stand was declared a national historic landmark in 1985.
The propulsion test stand is part of a controlled access area. It was built in 1957, and was used to test the Saturn Rockets. The test stand was declared a National Historic Landmark in 1985.
Building 4600 was the first LEED®-certified facility built by NASA. The complex is home to Marshall’s Materials and Processes Laboratory and its Spacecraft and Vehicle Systems Department.
The HOSC is a controlled access facility. It is NASA's 24/7 command post for space station science.

This test stand is part of a controlled access area. The stand was first used in 1965 for testing components of the Saturn 5 rocket. The stand was then modified several times to accomodate different testing purposes. As of 2019 the stand is in use by Blue Origin.

From clean welds on NASA's Space Launch System to clean air and water on the International Space Station, get a 360° look around two of the high bay facilities that make human space exploration possible
